Everything that Kristen Fenty had been trying to push out of her head was true. She began to wail. Gretchen came over and took the baby. end
No, Kristen realized. There's someone there. She opened the door. Two men. An Army chaplain and a Lt. Col. who was a friend of Joe's. /
Through the top panes of the front door she saw the screen door swing open. Maybe that's just the wind blowing the door, she thought /
Kristen heard something at the screen door. Maybe that's just the heater clicking on, she thought. /
Gretchen showed up at Kristen's door bright and early the next morning. "Was it Joe?" Kristen asked. "I'm just a wife," Gretchen said. /
Moreover, Fenty's remains were among the last to be found because he had been strapped into the inner cockpit of the smoldering Chinook /
Official notification had been delayed because recovery and identification of the men's bodies took longer than normal. /
Gretchen drove home and woke up her mother in law, who was staying with them. "She still doesn't know," she said. /
Kristen grew suspicious, so she called the rear-detachment commander, but got nothing. By midnight, Gretchen went home. /
Gretchen began to wonder if she had dreamt the conversation she'd had w/her husband. Then on TV cable news reported the chopper crash. /
They made small talk as Kristen put together care packages to send to Joe and tended to their newborn baby. It was all so surreal. /
Gretchen shook as she walked up to the Fentys' home. But when Kristen answered, it was clear she had not yet been told Joe was gone. /
The point was to get Gretchen back to Fort Drum asap so she could be there for Kristen when the news came in. She zoomed from PA to NY /
MAJ Richard Timmons' wife Gretchen was close w/Kristen, but was away on a family trip. Timmons, with permission, called his wife /
All men were killed, including Lt Col. Joe Fenty. Everyone was devastated. And what about Kristen who had just had their baby? /
The men from Able Troop began sliding down into the valley to try to save any survivors. They could smell flesh burning. /
The Chinook fell down the cliff, hitting the ground feet below and eloding, rolling down the hill, clearing everything in its path /
The back blade eloded, coming off the chopper. The men of Able dove for cover as shrapnel sprayed. The Chinook pitched forward and up. /
At :09 Totten tried to stick another landing, but the rear rotor hit a tree that the men from Able had tried for days to cut down. /
"I'm having trouble keeping it on the LZ" (Landing Zone) said the pilot, Chief Warrant Officer Eric W. Totten. …
It was windy and the PZ was tough to land. Everyone was wearing night vision goggles. The men from Able loaded supplies onto the bird /
At :36 pm the aircraft took off to land at a makeshift landing zone atop a mountain, PZ Reds, to extract the men of Able Troop. /
On May , , at :38 p.m., the Chinook, accompanied by Apaches, took off from Bagram, then to Jalalabad to pick up Fenty and refuel. /
Before he left he called Kristen. "What does Lauren look like?" he asked about their baby. "She has red hair." Lauren let out a wail. /
Fenty was going to come on a Chinook to supervise. He was worried. "I believe the real enemy out there will be the terrain," Fenty said. /
Before the operation began, Kristen went into labor. Via Army wives, Joe heard the news and called right as their baby was born /
That he was. His men, from -71 CAV, were scattered throughout the mountainous Korengal region but it was now time to exfil. /
Their little girl was due in April. "The timing is awful," Joe emailed home. "I'm going to be at the most remote place on the due date" /
Lt Col Fenty met Kristen in college, during Spring Break. years later, in , he'd deployed to Afghanistan. Kristen was pregnant. /2
There's a story I think about every Memorial Day. It's about Kristen and Joe Fenty. /1
